Using KinD (Kubernetes in Docker) to run Antidote.

See https://kind.sigs.k8s.io/ for more details about KinD

Download the kind CLI command, following the docs, for instance:

$ curl -Lo ./kind https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/kind/releases/download/v0.5.1/kind-$(uname)-amd64
$ chmod +x ./kind

Set the path to the tool:

$ export KIND=$(pwd)/kind

Then modify the kind-config.yaml file to adjust the path of the
curriculum repo, in the 'extraMounts.hostPath' setting, to point to
the absolute path to where the repo is checked-out.

The directory will be mounted into the kind node under /antidote,
allowing to work on lesson content.

You can now start the cluster with :

$ $KIND --loglevel info create cluster --config kind-config.yaml

Once it's booted, set the KUBECONFIG var for kubectl to use:

$ export KUBECONFIG="$(kind/kind get kubeconfig-path --name="kind")"

Set also set KUBECTL to point to the kubectl command :
$ export KUBECTL=...path/to/kubectl

You can then start the Antidote platorm over KinD using :
$ ./start.sh

Check the progress with $
$ $KUBECTL get -A all

When the syringe, antidote-web and ingress services are all up,
connect to : http://localhost:30001/

Stop the cluster with:
$ $KIND --loglevel info delete cluster

Enjoy :-)
